DAY 10 — COMPLETE OVERVIEW
🧠 1) PYTHON OOP BASICS
Core Concepts
Classes & Objects
Define a class, create objects, understand attributes vs methods
class Account:
    def __init__(self, account_id, balance):
        self.account_id = account_id
        self.balance = balance

    def deposit(self, amount):
        self.balance += amount

acc = Account(101, 1000)
acc.deposit(500)
Encapsulation
Private/protected attributes (_attr, __attr)
Getter/Setter methods for controlled access
Inheritance
Reuse code via subclasses
class SavingsAccount(Account):
    def __init__(self, account_id, balance, interest_rate):
        super().__init__(account_id, balance)
        self.interest_rate = interest_rate
Polymorphism
Method overriding in child classes
Operator overloading
Abstraction
Hide implementation details using abstract base classes (ABC module)
Real-Time Usage
Modeling users, accounts, trades, or microservices
Enforce rules via class methods (e.g., prevent overdraft)
GS-Level Scenario Questions
Design a Bank Account system with multiple account types. How would you model deposit/withdraw operations safely?
How do you enforce business rules like max withdrawal per day using OOP concepts?
How do you extend functionality without breaking existing code (polymorphism & inheritance)?
How would you serialize OOP objects for JSON logging or API responses?
🧠 2) DSA — STACK BASICS
Core Concepts
Stack = LIFO data structure
Operations: push, pop, peek, isEmpty
stack = []

# push
stack.append(10)

# pop
top = stack.pop()

# peek
top = stack[-1] if stack else None
Implement using list, deque, or linked list
Real-Time Usage
Undo/Redo operations in apps
Function call tracking (runtime stack)
Evaluate arithmetic expressions, parentheses matching
Backtracking problems (DFS in trading scenarios, graph search)
GS-Level Scenario Questions
Implement a real-time expression evaluator using stack.
Monitor function call stack for API tracing or error detection.
How would you optimize memory when millions of trades/events are pushed onto a stack?
Stack vs Queue: When would you prefer one over the other in trading system workflows?
🧠 3) PRODUCTION — CODE STRUCTURE
Core Concepts
Modular design: separate concerns in modules & packages
Layered structure:
models → data classes (OOP objects)
services → business logic
controllers → API endpoints / CLI
utils → helpers and common functions
logs → centralized logging
Naming conventions and folder organization
Real-Time Usage:
banking_app/
│
├─ models/
│   └─ account.py
├─ services/
│   └─ transaction_service.py
├─ controllers/
│   └─ account_controller.py
├─ utils/
│   └─ validators.py
├─ tests/
│   └─ test_account.py
└─ main.py
Error handling and logging per module
Easier for testing, deployment, and CI/CD
GS-Level Scenario Questions
You are building a CLI Banking App. How would you organize folders and classes for maintainability?
How would you structure code to add new microservices (trading, notification) later?
How do you ensure code readability and debug-ability in production?
How would you separate logging, validation, and business logic to avoid tight coupling?
